-+/* ===================================================================
-+   FIX 5 — REMAINING FIXED-SIZE TEXT (hero stat numbers, "Who We Are",
-+   "Comprehensive Educational Solutions", services number + title)
-+   Problem this solves: fix-zoomed-in-headings/fix2 converted most big
-+   headings to clamp() (.heading-fluid-*), but a handful of elements
-+   were missed and still used plain `text-Nxl md:text-Mxl` (or no
-+   responsive variant at all). Those jump straight to their largest
-+   Tailwind size at the 768px breakpoint and then stay that exact size
-+   all the way up to a 4K monitor — so a 1366–1440px laptop renders the
-+   identical pixel size as a 1920px+ screen, which reads as "too big"
-+   on the smaller laptop relative to how much room it actually has.
-+
-+   Each class below only overrides font-size (not weight/line-height/
-+   letter-spacing, which stay controlled by whatever Tailwind classes
-+   are already on the element) and its clamp() max equals the original
-+   fixed size — so on a large screen the text renders at exactly the
-+   same size as before; only the in-between laptop widths now scale
-+   smoothly instead of being pinned at the max.
-+   ================================================================ */
-+.heading-fluid-60 {
-+  font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 2.12rem + 1.63vw, 3.75rem) !important;
-+}
-+.heading-fluid-72 {
-+  font-size: clamp(3rem, 2.54rem + 1.96vw, 4.5rem) !important;
-+}
-+.heading-fluid-96 {
-+  font-size: clamp(3.5rem, 2.73rem + 3.27vw, 6rem) !important;
-+}
-+
-+/* ===================================================================
-+   FIX 6 — AUTO "ZOOM" FOR LAPTOP-WIDTH SCREENS
-+   Problem this solves: even with fluid headings, a LOT of this page
-+   (card widths, paddings, gaps, image sizes, decorative blobs) is
-+   still built with fixed px/rem values tuned for one specific screen
-+   width. Manually zooming the browser to 80% shrinks EVERYTHING
-+   uniformly (not just text) and was confirmed to look correct on
-+   smaller laptop screens — so we replicate that automatically.
-+
-+   Why `zoom` and not `transform: scale()`:
-+   `zoom` actually changes layout (siblings/page height reflow to the
-+   new size, so there's no leftover blank space), and it doesn't break
-+   `position: fixed` elements the way `transform: scale()` on a wrapper
-+   would — both matter here since the navbar is `fixed`. `zoom` lacked
-+   reliable Firefox support until version 126 (2024); it's safe to rely
-+   on now.
-+
-+   ASSUMPTION TO VERIFY: this assumes your own ("looks perfect") screen
-+   is >=1600px wide and the problem laptops are in the 1024–1599px
-+   range. If your own screen is narrower than 1600px, lower the 1600
-+   below to match it (or this rule will zoom YOUR screen out too).
-+   The breakpoint numbers are just CSS — change the px values freely.
-+   ================================================================ */
-+@media (min-width: 1024px) and (max-width: 1599px) {
-+  html {
-+    zoom: 0.75;
-+  }
-+}
-+
-+/* Optional: zoom IN slightly on very large/ultra-wide monitors.
-+   Comment this block out if you don't want anything above 100%. */
-+@media (min-width: 2560px) {
-+  html {
-+    zoom: 1.1;
-+  }
-+}
-+
